[3] Norovirus, suspected - hotel USA (Chicago)
Date: Tue 7 Feb 2006
From: Alfonso Rodriguez <ajrm_msds@yahoo.es>
Source: Chicago Tribune, News, Tue 7 Feb 2006 [edited]
<http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/chi-060207drake,1,2732866.st
ory?track=rss>

USA (MI): Virus sickens dozens at Hotel in Chicago
-----------------------------------------------
More than 100 guests, workers and attendees of a fundraising event at
the Drake Hotel on Chicago's Near North Side became ill over the
weekend [4-5 Feb 2006], sickened by what health officials say was an
ingested virus.
The outbreak was linked to a "norovirus" that caused nasty stomach
symptoms, including nausea, vomiting and diarrhea, said Tim Hadac,
spokesman for the Chicago Department of Public Health. Hadac said
none of the afflicted had reported any serious complications, and
though several people went to local hospital emergency rooms seeking
treatment, none had to be admitted.
"We have worked with the hotel to essentially order a top-to-bottom
scrubbing of not only the kitchens, but the entire hotel," Hadac
said. He added that officials continue to investigate, and the source
of the virus has not yet been found.
Drake officials today [7 Feb 2006] issued a statement confirming "a
number of guests and employees" became ill starting Friday [3 Feb
2006]. The hotel is working with the city to find the cause, the
statement said. General Manager Gregor Andreewitch said the hotel
today was operating normally, and all of its kitchens and restaurants
were open. He said he was not aware of anyone needing
hospitalization, but added, "We have asked whoever has become ill to
see a medical doctor."
Neither Andreewitch nor Drake spokesman Robert Allegrini could recall
any similar outbreaks in the hotel's past. "We're a hotel that's
known for its sterling reputation," Allegrini said. "As such, this is
an anomaly."
Sue Wilson, co-founder of the Children's Medical Research Foundation,
said her organization was holding an annual fundraiser, the
Sweetheart Dinner-Dance, at the hotel on Friday [3 Feb 2006] night.
The evening included a full menu of hors d'oeuvre and entrees, she
said. On Saturday afternoon, disturbing calls began to trickle in. By
Sunday, it was a flood.
"My 1st assumption of course was, 'Oh my goodness, great, we have the
flu,'" said Wilson, whose foundation gathers funding and support for
research into Sanfilipo Syndrome and other children's diseases. "But
when I started getting calls from guests, my concern level went up,
and I called the Drake." Several people reported going to the
hospital for dehydration, Wilson said. "It's a vicious one, whatever
it is," she said. "I'm very concerned about our guests."
According to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention,
noroviruses usually cause symptoms 12 to 48 hours after exposure.
Most people recover within a few days, and dehydration often is the
worst side effect. The virus must be ingested and most often is
transmitted through contaminated food or drink, according to the CDC.
Its spread can be prevented through careful sanitation, cleaning and
hand-washing. Hotels, cruise ships and other settings with
large-scale accommodations are the most common locations for
outbreaks, according to the CDC. In 2004, more than 1000 guests and
workers at the Flamingo Hotel in Las Vegas fell ill to the virus. And
more than 1100 may have been infected in September 2005 in the
aftermath of Hurricane Katrina, according to the Journal of the
American Medical Association.
[Byline: Gerry Doyle]
